TUNNEL RAT<br><br>
Tunnel rat - A creature that crawls into a deep dark hole with<br>
 no more than a pistol, a flashlight, and maybe a knife, to seek <br>
the light at the other end of the tunnel, if there is one, or any <br>
thing in between the beginning and the end.<br><br>
The Tunnels of Cu Chi. Yeah, I was there in ‘69 - ‘70. I wasn’t<br>
 a “full-time” tunnel rat, but I crawled through my share of them.<br>
 It was a most exciting, adrenaline pumping, dangerous, and<br>
 sometimes humorous experience. It scares the hell out of me,<br>
 come to think of it.<br>
What do you want to know about a tunnel rat ?<br>
What made him do what he did ?<br>
What does he think about ?<br>
What scares him ?<br>
Why would anyone in his right mind do anything so unpredictable ?<br>
How does it feel to be trapped underground where you can’t go<br>
 forward or backward and the only things you can move are your<br>
 head and the arm holding the flashlight and all you can see are<br>
 boxes of ammo and a big snake ?!<br><br>
Getting back to the book, “The Tunnels Of Cu Chi”. Get it, read it. <br>
It will answer many questions. When you get to the section about<br>
 the discovery of a printing press, I can attest to the validity of the book.<br>
 I was there. Kermit Wayne “Pat” Garrett was a good friend. Still is,<br>
although I haven’t heard from him in few years.<br><br>
Yes, I agree that the subject would a good theme for a movie. <br>
I don’t know if I could/would go see it or not. A few years back I was<br>
 at Disney World in Florida with my family. My son went charging into<br>
 a complex from, I believe, a scene from the, “Honey, I Shrunk The Kids” <br>
movie or Sim Ant or something.  <br>
“Come on, Dad. Let’s go through this.”<br>
It was a series of tunnels. I entered and after the first bend, <br>
when I could no longer see the entrance, it closed in on me. <br>
I was back in a tunnel in Viet Nam. It scared me so badly that when<br>
I backed out and turned to my wife, she ask what was wrong. <br>
I was as white as a sheet she said. I could not go there. <br>
She said, “ It’s Viet Nam, isn’t it? It is O.K. not to do this.”<br><br>
Anyway, ask away. I and others will try to answer.<br>

